{
  "text": "where / denotes a mapping from the input space X D to a high-dimensional inner product feature space H D , i.e. / : x d 2 X D ! / x d \u00f0 \u00de 2 H D (the same holds for cell line kernel k c ). It is, however, possible to avoid explicit computation of the mapping / and define the kernel directly in terms of the original input features, such as gene expression profiles, by replacing the inner product h\u00c1; \u00c1i with an appropriately chosen kernel function (so-called kernel trick), e.g. the Gaussian kernel [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "35730151"
